{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493189"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1249"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1249"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.06,0.08,0.44,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115496"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1249"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97499"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"538"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2507"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11605"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43065"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47630"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115496"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a factory fire one hour ago. He managed to walk away from the scene but has been coughing persistently since. He also complains of a headache. He has a medical history of hypertension and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His medications include perindopril and as-needed salbutamol. On examination, he appears confused and disoriented with a pulse rate of 92/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Soot is present over his lips but there are no external signs of airway injury, such as swelling of the oropharynx or hoarseness of voice. There is no stridor or increased work of breathing. His chest is clear on auscultation. Arterial blood gas shows pH 7.38 (7.35-7.45), PaO2 85 mmHg (80-100), PaCO2 42 mmHg (35-45).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nebulised salbutamol","Nebulised ipratropium","Intravenous hydrocortisone","High-flow oxygen","Sedation for intubation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s headache, disorientation, and soot on lips after a factory fire should raise the suspicion of smoke inhalation and carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning. While there is no definitive evidence of an oropharyngeal burn in this patient (no swelling of the oropharynx or hoarseness), the presence of soot on the lips is concerning for smoke exposure and possible inhalation injury. Indoor fires, especially fires associated with chemical industry explosion, should raise the suspicion of carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning. CO poisoning presents with headache, confusion, nausea, and disorientation. Notably, the arterial blood gas results appear normal, but this does not exclude carbon monoxide poisoning as the PaO2 reflects dissolved oxygen in plasma, not the oxygen-carrying capacity of haemoglobin which is impaired when CO binds to form carboxyhaemoglobin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOxygen saturation is a poor indicator of CO concentration since pulse oximeter cannot differentiate between oxyhaemoglobin and carboxyhaemoglobin. All patients with suspected smoke inhalation or possible CO exposure should be given \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-flow oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E via facemask to prevent severe respiratory compromise and to facilitate the elimination of CO. Clinical indicators of thermal or smoke inhalation include burns on the face, singeing of the eyebrows, soot on the lips or inside the oral cavity, stridor, and carboxyhaemoglobin level \u003E10%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESedation for intubation\u003C/strong\u003E may be required for patients with clinical symptoms or indicators of upper airway oedema (e.g., hoarseness of the voice, stridor, inflammation of the oropharyngeal membrane). This patient does not have any clinical indicator of upper airway damage and does not require intubation at the moment. Intubation should be considered if any of the above signs are present which typically occur due to an explosion in a confined space. However, high-flow oxygen should be administered to all patients who potentially require intubation anyway as pre-oxygenation as part of either a rapid sequence or routine intubation and therefore this would be instituted in this patient regardless of potential future airway issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised salbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eipratropium\u003C/strong\u003E are indicated in patients with COPD exacerbation. Considering this patient\u0027s recent history, his clinical symptoms are unlikely to be due to COPD exacerbation but rather to smoke inhalation and possible CO poisoning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in patients with severe asthma exacerbation or anaphylaxis. While corticosteroids have been studied in acute lung injury, they are not part of the immediate management of smoke inhalation. The priority in this case is addressing potential carbon monoxide poisoning and ensuring adequate oxygenation, not treating inflammatory responses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["High-flow oxygen is the immediate management for suspected carbon monoxide poisoning regardless of oxygen saturation readings.","Pulse oximetry cannot differentiate between oxyhaemoglobin and carboxyhaemoglobin, making it unreliable in carbon monoxide poisoning.","Clinical indicators of inhalation injury include facial burns, singed eyebrows, soot in the mouth, stridor, and elevated carboxyhaemoglobin levels."],"references":["Rehberg S, Maybauer MO, Enkhbaatar P, Maybauer DM, Yamamoto Y, Traber DL. Pathophysiology, management and treatment of smoke inhalation injury. Expert Rev Respir Med. 2009 Jun 1;3(3):283-297. doi: 10.1586/ERS.09.21. PMID: 20161170; PMCID: PMC2722076."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97499"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1249"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97499"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T09:19:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T09:20:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1249"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115496"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"up